4 H20-30. Limits on lobbying. Lobbying on the House floor and in the anteroom is prohibited during a
5 daily session, 2 hours before the session, and 2 hours after the session. A registered lobbyist is prohibited from
6 the house floor.
7 H20-40. Admittance to the House floor. (1) The following persons may be admitted to the House floor
8 during a daily session: present legislators and former legislators who are not registered lobbyists; legislative
9 employees necessary for the conduct of the session; registered media representatives; and members' spouses
10 and children. The Speaker may allow exceptions to this rule.
11 (2) Only a member may sit in a member's chair when the House is in session.
12 H20-50. Dilatory motions or questions -- appeal. The House has a right to protect itself from dilatory
13 motions or questions used for the purpose of delaying or obstructing business. The presiding officer shall
14 decide if motions (except a call of the House) or questions are dilatory. This decision may be appealed to the
15 House for a determination by majority vote.
16 H20-60. Lobbying by employees -- sanctions. (1) A legislative employee or aide of either house is
17 prohibited from lobbying, although a legislative committee may request testimony from a person so restricted.
18 (2) The Speaker may discipline or discharge any House employee violating this prohibition. The
19 Speaker may withdraw the privileges of any House aide violating this prohibition.
20 H20-70. Papers distributed on desks -- exception. A paper concerning proposed legislation may not
21 be placed on representatives' desks unless it is authorized by a member and permission has been granted by
22 the Speaker. The Sergeant-at-Arms shall direct its distribution. This restriction does not apply to material
23 prepared by staff and placed on a representative's desk at the request of the representative.
24 H20-80. Violation of rules -- procedure -- appeal. (1) If a member, in speaking or otherwise, violates
25 the rules of the House, the Speaker shall, or the majority or minority leader may, call the member to order, in
26 which case the member called to order must be seated immediately.
27 (2) The member called to order may move for an appeal to the House. The matter must be submitted to
28 the House for determination by majority vote. The motion is nondebatable.
